Plant-derived fungi are of great interest to both chemical and agricultural researchers, due to both their role as a source of potential drug leads, and their ecological importance (

). 

Colletotrichum

is a widely-distributed genus of important plant-associated fungi: although members of the genus are best-known as plant pathogens, many 

Colletotrichum
species

are harmless and, in some cases, they can be beneficial to plants (Barth´elemy et al., 2020; 

). 

found that the presence of 

Colletotrichum tofieldiae

in the roots of the plant 

Arabidopsis thaliana

enhanced the fitness of the host. Species of 

Colletotrichum

are known to produce diverse metabolites, such as polyketides, peptides, alkaloids, and terpenoids (

; 

; 

; 

; 

), with biological activities including antimicrobial, cytotoxic, phytotoxic, antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). 

Colletotrichum brevisporum

is a recently-discovered member of the genus, first reported in 
2012 in
Thailand
, from plant leaves that were infected by anthracnose (

). Later, this species was found to cause anthracnose in a range of agriculturally important plant species, including papaya fruit, chaoyote, pumpkins (

; 

; 

), etc. Overall, the majority of scientific studies on this species have focused on its role in plant disease, rather than its potential as a source of chemical diversity.

The fungus
Colletotrichum brevisporum PSSF
01 was obtained from the plant
Piper sarmentosum Roxb. (Piperaceae)
, collected in Guangxi , China . The fungus was cultured in Potato Dextrose Broth for 10 days, and both biomass and supernatant extracted with organic solvents to yield an organic extract. The extract was fractionated by a combination of solvent-solvent partition, silica gel column chromatography, and semipreparative reverse phase HPLC , to yield seven undescribed bianthrones, the brevianthrones ( 1–7 ), along with two structurally related anthraquinones. The anthraquinones were identified as nalgiovensin ( 8 ) and 1-methoxy-nalgiovensin ( 9 ) by comparing their HRMS data, UV spectra, and 1 H and 13 C NMR data with literature values (
;
;
;
;
). Comparison of optical rotation data with literature values confirmed that both anthraquinones possessed S -configuration at the C-12 position (see Fig. 1 ).

The number of possible isomers for bianthrones depends on a number of factors. In homobianthrones, where each anthrone half is substituted by the same achiral groups, three possible isomers exist: two enantiomers and the meso -isomer. This is the case for the homodimeric brevianthrones A1-A3 ( 1-3 ): the pseudo -meso isomer, brevianthrone A3 ( 3 ), would be expected to be found in twice the amount as the two pseudoenantiomers ( 1 , 2 ), as there are two ways to form the pseudo - meso isomer in a non-stereospecific dimerization process: the 10 S , 10 ′ R and 10 R , 10 ′ S fusions produce the same compound. This is in line with the results from chiral HPLC ( Fig. S2 ), and with the ratios observed for the related allianthrones (
). In the heterobianthrones, where the two anthrone subunits have different structures, there will be four stereoisomeric possibilities, all present in equal amounts, as was observed for brevianthrones B1–B4 ( 4–7 ). If there are chiral substituents, the situation becomes more complex (
). Each of the brevianthrones possesses four chiral centers and has chiral centers in the side-chains, leading to a large number of possible isomers; however, based on the known absolute configurations of the anthraquinones 8 and 9 , and for brevianthrone A1 ( 1 ), the S -configuration was assigned to the 12 and 12 ′ positions of the remaining bianthrones ( 2–7 ), simplifying the analysis.

Determining the absolute configurations at the 10 and 10 ′ positions was more challenging. Determining absolute configuration of bianthrones can be conducted through a variety of methods.
developed a method to determine relative configuration based on 1 H-NMR. In a 2009 report, using NMR shift calculation and use of the CP3 parameter, which compares differences in calculated shift with differences in experimental shift, experimental spectra could be assigned to two diastereomers (
); this method was subsequently applied by
. However, the most commonly used methods are X-ray crystallography and electronic circular dichroism (ECD), which were used in a 2018 study in determining the absolute configurations of the allianthrones (
).

The allianthrones, isolated from a marine-derived
Aspergillus alliaceus
strain by
were similar to compounds 1–3 , except for the presence of a chlorine atom in position 2. To determine whether
Colletotrichum brevisporum
could produce analogous metabolites incorporating halogen atoms, experiments were conducted in media enriched in halide salts. Similar enrichment studies have been successful in producing additional analogues in other fungi (
;
). The fungus was grown in the presence of NaCl, NaBr and KI (2%), however, according to the HPLC analysis, no new peaks were detected compared to the controls, suggesting that this fungus lacked a suitable halogenase capable of producing halogenated bianthrones. Halogenase enzymes are common in microorganisms isolated from marine environments (
), where higher levels of halide salts are present. Thus, the difference in biosynthetic capability of the two fungi might be attributed to the different environments from which they were isolated.

Anthraquinones are abundant in plants, lichens and fungi, with more than 700 examples in the literature (

). Anthraquinones have been shown to possess biological activities like cytotoxic, antimicrobial, and anti-diabetic activities, and are also applied in the dyeing industry (

; 

; 

). Anthraquinones have been reported from the 

Colletotrichum

genus before; several anthraquinones from the endophytic fungus 

Colletotrichum
sp.

JS-0367 possessed significant neuroprotective activity (

). Bianthrones are a class of compound formed by fusion of two anthrone precursors. Much rarer than the anthraquinones, these compounds have been reported in plants, animals and fungi (

). The naturally-occurring bianthrones tend to be substituted by methyl, hydroxy, methoxy groups, and occasionally more complex substituents. Studies have shown that bianthrones can exhibit potent biological activity, for example cytotoxicity against a range of cancer cell lines (

; 

), antifungal properties (

), and antiplasmodial activity against 

Plasmodium falciparum
(
Ndjakou Lenta et al., 2008
)

. While the biosynthesis of anthraquinones have been well-studied in several fungi (

), the biosynthesis of bianthrones has been far less well studied in microbes. The ratios of stereoisomers produced in the current study is consistent with a non-stereospecific dimerization mechanism, though whether this is enzyme catalyzed or spontaneous is unknown.

